The user is saying that on mobile, when they long-press (touch start) to open the picker, and then release (touch end), the picker disappears. Let me look at the touch handling code.

Looking at the current `ReactionButton.jsx`:

```js
const handleTouchStart = useCallback(() => {
    longPressTimerRef.current = setTimeout(() => {
        setShowPicker(true);
    }, 500);
}, []);

const handleTouchEnd = useCallback(() => {
    if (longPressTimerRef.current) {
        clearTimeout(longPressTimerRef.current);
        longPressTimerRef.current = null;
    }
}, []);
```

The `handleTouchEnd` clears the long press timer, but doesn't close the picker. So if the user holds for 500ms, the picker opens. When they release, `handleTouchEnd` fires but only clears the timer (which already fired).

But wait - on mobile touch devices, after `touchend`, the browser may also fire `mouseLeave` or `click` events. The `handleQuickClick` function is checking conditions...

Continuing with the click handler logic...

So after a long press opens the picker, the subsequent click event fires and closes it again because `showPicker` is true. That's the bug. I need to prevent the click from closing the picker if it was just opened by a long press. I can track this with a flag that gets set when the picker opens via long press, then in `handleQuickClick` I check that flag and skip the close logic if it's set.

Setting up a flag-based approach... Writing event handlers...

